The problem, of course, is that BITNET doesn't fall within the definitions of
what a domain should be (at least the way that folks are using the .BITNET
pseudo-domain).  We have a 3 hosts here at Maryland on BITNET.  They are also
on the Internet.  Clearly, they shouldn't have two different names.  We
name them in the .UMD.EDU domain.

There is at least on host at Towsen State University (also in the state of
Maryland) on BITNET, but it is *only* on BITNET.  It is named in the
TOWSON.EDU domain.  It seems that this solution is one that works best.
They have a few MX records such that mail to them is arranged to be send via
a BITNET - Internet mail gateway.  Soon they will be connected to the
Internet, and all they need change is a few MX records and now folks can
send them mail directly, rather than continue to use the (rather busy)
BITNET - Internet mail gateways. 

louie

